				<p><b>Everything That Rises<br>Randolph Peters</b></p>

				<p><i>This piece was premiered by the MCO last season. The composer has provided the following note:</i></p>

				<p>The idea behind this piece refers to French philosopher Pierre Teilhard de Chardin&rsquo;s conception of &lsquo;Omega Point&rsquo; (from Faith in Man (1947) and The Future of Man (1959):</p>

				<p>&ldquo;Remain true to yourself, but move ever upward toward greater consciousness and greater love! At the summit you will find yourselves united with all those who, from every direction, have made the same ascent. For everything that rises must converge.&rdquo;</p>

				<p><b>Piano Concerto No. 4, in G Major, Op. 58<br>Ludwig van Beethoven</b></p>

				<p>As with the symphony, Beethoven&rsquo;s makeover process on the concerto was a gradual one. First, there were lessons to learn and dues to pay. He arrived in Vienna at the end of 1792, intending merely to finish his musical education with Haydn before returning to Bonn. Circumstances, his magnificent talents in particular, led him to change those plans. The Austrian capital was destined to be the centre of his activities for the rest of his life.</p>

				<p>He won his first fame in Vienna as a pianist, performing in the city&rsquo;s fashionable salons and concert rooms. He gradually made a name for himself through his bold performing style, which, as with Mozart, included a brilliant talent for improvisation. During this period, he composed solo piano works for his own performance. He revised certain of his existing creations as well, including the Piano Concerto in B-flat Major. His first fully completed work of this kind, he may have begun it as early as 1788, in Bonn. It was the earliest orchestral work that he was prepared to acknowledge (a Concerto in E-flat Major &lsquo;for harpsichord or piano,&rsquo; dates from approximately a decade earlier. It exists only in a version where the orchestral part has been arranged for piano). The much-revised B-flat Concerto was published in 1801 as &lsquo;No. 2.&rsquo; Concerto &lsquo;No. 1&rsquo; had been published in 1797, and No. 3 in C Minor followed in 1803.</p>

				<p>He composed the exceptionally beautiful Concerto No. 4 in 1805 and 1806. During this astonishingly fertile period, he also produced the Fourth Symphony and the Violin Concerto, pieces which share the piano concerto&rsquo;s contented nature. As he had done with his three previous piano concertos, he played the first performance himself, in March 1807, before an aristocratic audience in the Vienna home of his friend, Prince Lobkowitz. Listeners responded with only polite applause, and the public debut proved even less successful. It was only when no less a piano soloist than Felix Mendelssohn took it up during the 1830s that it finally began to make its mark.</p>

				<p>Its very beginning is one of its most arresting features. The piano, rather than the orchestra, has the first word, and it enters not with crashing chords (that salvo would have to wait for the &lsquo;Emperor&rsquo; Concerto, No. 5), but with simple, gentle phrases. The effect is magical, establishing the opening movement&rsquo;s tranquil mood with one brief, telling stroke.</p>

				<p>The brief second movement is another gem. It has been said to evoke the mythological Orpheus taming wild beasts with his lyre. The orchestra&rsquo;s lower strings begin the conversation gruffly. The piano responds with soothing caresses. The orchestra&rsquo;s protestations gradually lose steam until the soloist delivers such an impassioned plea for conciliation that the orchestra can only meekly capitulate. The concluding, high-spirited rondo follows on without a break. It is the most conventional part of the concerto, but Beethoven peppered it with enough individual touches of humour and instrumental colour (introducing trumpets and timpani into the concerto for the first time) to ensure it is worthy of the preceding movements.</p>

				<p><b>Flanders Fields Reflections<br>John Burge</b></p>

				<p>This piece for string orchestra was commissioned by Sinfonia Toronto and was premiered by that ensemble in 2006. When it was released on CD three years later (Marquis), it won the Juno Award for Best Classical Composition.</p>

				<p>It was inspired by the famous poem that Canadian physician John McCrae wrote in 1915, while he was serving war duty in Belgium. Each of the five movements reflects upon a specific phrase from the poem.</p>

				<ol>
				<li><i>The Poppies Blow</i>: The music captures the melancholy tone of the poem, while imitating the sighing of the wind across the field and through the flowers.</li>
				<li><i>Still Bravely Singing</i>: A solo violin speaks for the gentle larks, all the other strings for the conflict raging below.</li>
				<li><i>We Are the Dead</i>: Burge pays tribute to the slain soldiers with a funeral march whose restraint makes it all the more poignant.</li>
				<li><i>Loved and Were Loved</i>: To counter the preceding movement, Burge offers an outpouring of warm emotion to portray the love that filled the lives of those who died in combat&thinsp;&mdash;&thinsp;love both offered and received.</li>
				<li><i>We Shall Not Sleep</i>: This gently flowing finale skillfully mingles reflection with glimmers of hope for a better, wiser future.</li>
			</ol>

